  Reptiles(
      category: "Reptiles",
      title: "BlueTounge\nSkink",
      image:
      "assets/Reptiles/bluetongue.png",
      image2:
      'assets/Reptiles/bluetongue2.jpg',
      subtitle:
      "The Blue Tongue Skink is a group of fat-bodied bengkarung that has the characteristic feature of blue or indigo tongue. These lizards are widespread in the Maluku islands, Papua, to Australia.",
      description:
      "All types of this genus have a solid body but somewhat flattened. The body is mottled brown or gray and dark, except for Tiliqua nigrolutea and Tiliqua rugosa. As the name implies, these lizards have broad tongues and are dark blue or bluish black in color. This lizard will stick out its tongue if disturbed, with the intention that the intruder thinks that this lizard is poisonous and then leaves it. These lizards move quite slowly compared to other types of lizards. These lizards like insects, small arachnids, vegetables, and fruits as food. Almost all species are distributed in Australia, except for Tiliqua gigas which is only found in Maluku and Papua. These lizards reproduce by laying eggs in their stomachs and giving birth (Ovoviviparous). These lizards usually give birth to as many as 5-10 tails, the number of children of each species is different. The eggs will hatch in the stomach after incubation between 3 to 5 months. The length of the newly hatched young lizard reaches about 13 cm.\n Indonesian Blue Tongue Skinks are 15-30” long (38-76 centimeters) and weigh around 700 grams. They are typically smaller than Northerns. All blue-tongued skinks have long bodies, short, thick tails, short legs, triangular heads, and of course blue tongues. Tanimbars are silver, grey, or yellow in color, with hard and glossy scales. Classic Indonesians are distinguished by their green or yellowish coloring, solid black forelimbs, speckling between bands, and thin black head markings. Meraukes have a salmon or orange-colored belly, freckling on their arms, and distinct banding typically without freckling in between the bands. Irian Jayas have speckled forearms, brown banding, and minimal speckling in between the bands. Kei Island BTS have unique freckles from their head down their back.\nBlue-tongued skinks are fairly large lizards, reaching 18 to 20 inches in length. They have long, solid bodies, triangular-shaped heads and comparatively small legs. The tail is slightly shorter than the length of the body and tapers to a point. There are several species of blue-tongued skinks inhabiting Australia and Indonesia, which all differ slightly in appearance. Indonesian blue-tongued skinks vary in color among individuals but are generally grey or pale brown with irregular dark brown or black bands across the back and tail. Their legs are mostly black with small specks of white. They are also equipped with a blue tongue.\n\nUnlike most reptile species, these skinks do not lay eggs. Instead they are ovoviviparous, meaning they give birth to live young encased in membranous sacs. Mating occurs in the spring months. Gestation lasts three to four months and results in five to 15 young. Neonates are able to feed on their own after birth and are reared quickly.",
      habitat: "Indonesian blue-tongued skinks live in arid grasslands and dry sclerophyll forests. Their short legs do not allow them to climb easily, so they spend the vast majority of their time on the ground hiding in the brush or in shallow burrows carved by their shovel-like snouts. They are diurnal (active during the daytime) and they generally find cover to rest under at night. Even though skinks have very sturdy, solid tails, they can release them like some other lizard species. This is used as a defense mechanism when necessary. Their tails will heal over, sometimes growing back, but never reform exactly like the original. Blue-tongued skinks may also display their blue tongue when threatened.",
      diet: "Blue-tongued skinks are omnivorous, eating both animal and plant matter. In the wild, they eat fruit, insects, mollusks and carrion. At Happy Hollow, they are fed fruits, vegetables and insects.\n\nMost species are diurnal, ground-foraging omnivores, feeding on a wide variety of insects, gastropods, flowers, fruits and berries. The pygmy blue-tongue is again the exception, being primarily an ambush predator of terrestrial arthropods. All are viviparous, with litter sizes ranging from 1-4 in the pygmy blue-tongue and shingleback to 5-24 in the eastern and northern blue-tongues.",
